abstract: THERE is at hand a renaissance of the ballet in America. We have had signs and signs, but now it seems to have come. abstract: NEWPORT, R.I., Sept. 1 -- It was the most thoroughly rainy day of the season to-day. abstract: MONTREAL, Sept. 1 -- Kent and Daley of Boston, on a motor tandem, established a record here to-day for five miles, going the distance in 7:01 4-5. The race was two motor tandems against Champion's motor cycle. Champion's machine broke down. In the twenty-five-mile race between Champion of France and McEachren of Canada, the Canadian's wheel broke down in the second mile, and the Frenchman gained almost two laps.

abstract: PITTSBURG, Penn., Sept. 1 -- The principal interest in strike matters to-day was centred in the Duquesne plant, where it was expected the strikers would make a decided move toward closing down the entire works. abstract: CLEVELAND, Ohio, Sept. 1 -- With the breaking of dawn this morning the citizens of Cleveland awoke to look upon a scene of unparalleled devastation and destruction caused by a raging flood. abstract: BAR HARBOR, Me., Sept. 2. -- Mr. and Mrs. Thomas Huger Pratt of New York gave the first affair of the month at the Kebo Valley Club to-night. It was a large dinner and was followed by a cotillion. The entire house was decorated with palms and potted plants and cut flowers. The dinner was attended lay the elder set, and the cotillion, which was given for Miss Eleanor Sedley, brought all the young set.

abstract: UTICA, N.Y., Sept. 2. -- There were two Labor Day parades here to-day on account of four non-union bands which headed some of the labor organizations. They were the Italo-American Band, the Ashcraft Band of the Church of the Holy Cross, and two drum corps. There were two union bands in line, the Germania and Shremp's Bands, both members of the Musical Union, which is affiliated with the American Federation of Labor.

abstract: CINCINNATI, Ohio, Sept. 4. -- To enforce a demand for a uniform scale of wages and the restriction of the number of apprentices all the art glass workers in this city who are members of Glass Workers' Union No. 9 struck to-day. abstract: The return rush of New York's migratory population from village and mountain and seaside is on. The man with the dress suit case and the tan and the woman with the freckles and the heavily strapped trunk are coming back by tens of thousands, to take up the grind for another year. They are swarming out of every railway station in the city, and their belongings are choking up the baggage rooms.

abstract: NEWPORT, R.I., Sept. 8. -- The shooting, of President McKinley is quite effectually closing the Newport social season. On the night of the shooting nearly every dinner was abandoned. Saturday there was a change, and a number of large dinners were held as arranged, but the leading entertainment the dinner to have been given by Mr. and Mrs. Cornelius Vanderbilt -- was abandoned only a few minutes before the time for it to begin.

abstract: NEWPORT, Sept. 9 -- With the continued improvement in the President's condition and the probability of his ultimate recovery, society entertainments in Newport have been renewed, and to-night there were fully as many dinners as on any other night this season. abstract: BOSTON, Sept. 10 -- Miss Lydia L.A. Very, teacher and author, died at her home 154 Federal Street, Salem, this morning after a brief Illness. She was born in this city on Nov. 2, 1823. She was a teacher in the Salem public and private schools for thirty-four years. Among her books were "Sayings and Doings Among Insects and Flowers," "Slyph, the Organ Grinder's Daughter," "A Strange Disclosure," and "An Old-Fashioned Garden."

Dailey.

abstract: The grain market yesterday advanced much less than was expected in many quarters in view of the Government report on corn. Wheat opened strong and advanced half a cent, only to react to Tuesday night's figures on profit-taking. Selling orders were also executed for Chicago, because of the receipt of 958 cars in the Northwest, as against 438 cars last year, and, at primary points, 1,514,000 bushels, as against 1,318,000 bushels last year.

abstract: PITTSBURG, Penn., Sept. 11 -- The New York Council of the National Tube Company met with the local council at Pittsburg to-day to discuss the strike. It was announced that the council voted without taking final action and will probably meet again to-morrow. It was practically settled, however, that no long shut-down would be tolerated, and that the next attempt to start will be a determined one.

abstract: To the Editor of The New York Times: President McKinley's gunshot wound and its gangrenous condition are, in my opinion, ordinary. There was no poisoned bullet, excepting the poison naturally belonging to a dirty pistol ball fired at close range. The concussion alone at such proximity would be enough to destroy the outside tissues even if no powder grains went through the clothing.

abstract: PARIS, Sept. 17. -- By invitation of Gen. Porter, the United States Ambassador, resident and traveling Americans met at his residence this afternoon to adopt resolutions on the assassination of President McKinley. abstract: HARRISBURG, Penn., Sept. 17, (On Board the Funeral Train.) -- Leaving Washington the long, winding train bearing the body of the martyred President plunged out into the dark night, and hurried like a black streak on Its mournful Journey. abstract: To-day in New York will be given over to observances honoring the memory of President William McKinley. In all city churches there will be services. Mr. McKinley will be the subject of eulogy, and in many cases his favorite hymns will be features of the musical services. There will be no distinction as to denominations or creeds in these observances.

abstract: PRINCETON, N.J., Sept. 18. -- The annual openirig exercises of Princeton University were held in Alexander Hall this afternoon. The Faculty and Board of Trustees marched to the building from the university library. President Patton delivered the address to the undergraduates. He spoke feelingly of the death of President McKinley, and expressed the opinion that President Roosevelt would fill his high office efficiently.

abstract: CANTON, Ohio, Sept. 18. -- Those who had known William McKinley best to-day received his body at his old home. They had forgotten the illustrious career of the statesman in the loss of a great personal friend, who had grown dearer to them with the passing of the years. They hardly noticed the President of the United States or his Cabinet or the Generals or Admirals in their resplendent uniforms.

abstract: WASHINGTON, Sept. 19. -- Washington gave evidence to-day in most impressive manner that its heart was with Canton in the solemn hour of President McKinley's funeral. abstract: ORANGE, N.J., Sept. 19. -- Never has there been such an expression of sympathy as was shown in Orange to-day. Business was entirely suspended in retail stores and factories, and the saloons and bootblack shops closed at 10 o'clock and did not reopen until 4. It was no perfunctory closing of the saloons as is the case on holidays and Sundays.

abstract: PITTSBURG, Penn., Sept. 19. -- Experts are busy computing the cost of the strike to the steel corporation and to the workers. Gross earnings of the constituent companies have been cut off to the extent of nearly $15,000,000.

abstract: BOSTON, Sept. 20. -- At the Clearing House to-day balances between the banks loaned at 4 per cent, and the New York funds sold at 23 cents discount. These experiments and some inventions with the same aim are due, Mr. Mason says, to the unprecedented scarcity and high prices of fuel in the country last year.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Sept. 23 -- The local market did not escape depression to-day. The trading was monopolized by the Wall Street shares, notably Heading and United States Steel, which New York sold here in liberal quantities. Practically the whole market was lower. Pennsylvania fell 5/4, but the exclusively local shares kept close to Saturday's figures.

abstract: PRINCETON, N. J., Sept. 25 -- The undergraduates were disappointed this afternoon when they appeared at football practice and learned that the first line-up of the eleven was postponed for a day or two. abstract: TRENTON, N.J., Sept. 26. -- Franklin Murphy was placed in nomination for Governor of New Jersey by the Republican Convention here this afternoon. The nomination was by acclamation and not even a shadow of opposition developed. The platform adopted deplores President McKinley's death, commends the National and State administrations, and pledges the party, if continued in power, to the further reduction of taxes, to good roads, better schools, and legislation against anarchy.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Penn., Sept. 28 -- Pennsylvania ran up 28 points on Lehigh to-day in the opening game of the football season, while the Bethlehemites never once menaced the Quaker goal. In spite of threatening weather, something like 4,000 spectators turned out on Franklin Field. Despite the fact that the Red and Blue won, there was not much encouragement from the game, as Pennsylvania has a very light line, and its offensive play was lamentably weak.
